Well my day was going well until about 6 pm this evening.  That's what time my Martial Arts class starts.  Don't get me wrong, I love Martial Arts.  However, tonight was apparently just not my night.

Lia & I were hanging out at the beginning of class chatting.  We had to do an eval for the class.  Once we were done, Lia & I started chatting & goofing around.  Well, while she was sitting on the floor (which is a padded mat), I walked up to her & played like I was gonna stomp her ankles.  So I hopped up & kicked my left foot out like I was gonna stomp her but didn't.  

Apparently my feet didn't want to cooperate with me tonight.  When I came back down (with a majority of my weight on my right foot), I'm guessing I came down on the side of my right foot instead of flat footed.  Well this through my balance off causing me to side step my ankle (if you know what I mean by that then you understand what I did).  Seeing as how a majority of my weight was already on that leg, I begain to fall over on my already overturned ankle.  And as I collapse, what do I hear?

You guessed it...a POP!  Yep, my ankle popped.  Meaning that I have a very badly sprained ankle.  I had an atheletic (sp?) trainer look at my ankle & he says it's a Grade 1 Sprain (I believe that is how he phrased it) with major swelling.  So I've been icing it & keeping it wrapped.  Hopefully it'll be better in a week.

I'm just grateful it didn't break......again.  Night all.

~Tari

Hey guys...I'm still around.  Not too much going on around here.  I'm working some, so that's a plus.  Anyways...

Tonight was an awesome night.  I went to see Edwin McCain in concert with two of my friends.  It was great...I am currently on Cloud 12.  That's right...I'm too high for Cloud 9 but not high enough for Cloud 13.  That Cloud is currently roped off...not sure if or when I'll ever get back to that Cloud.

I love hearing Edwin McCain perform live.  He is a wonderful singer and a great songwriter and guitar-player.  Plus it is awesome to see and hear his fellow band members playing alongside him.  Seeing Larry Chaney, Dave Harrison, and Craig Shields playing helps bring to the foreground who these guys are and the instruments they play that we hear on Edwin's albums, instead of viewing it the other instruments as just background sound accompanying Edwin and his guitar.

Edwin McCain played several, several songs tonight (pretty much covering all my favorites and then some).  Hearing him live, he is able to give better to some of his songs that he just can't do in the studio.  It is awesome to hear how his songs sound on the albums and then hear him perform them live.  Half the time it's a totally different sound and feel.

This is now my fourth time seeing him in concert.  I now own pretty much all of his albums.  Is it bad that not only, upon hearing the beginning of his songs, I can tell you the name of the song as well as the album it is on??  I also bought one of his shirts that they were selling tonight.  I own one of his DVDs and I am working on getting his other one.  I am also going to be keeping up with his tour so I can find out the next time he will be in Nashville again.

If you have heard his music and like it, I'd suggest seeing him in concert.  It is a wonderful experience.  Also, in case some of you who are fans don't already know this, he has been picked up by a record label (Vangard Records) and his music is also being aired on 101.1 in Nashville...not sure how far that station reaches.  Check him out if you haven't already.  His music is great.

Well Set Strike was fun tonight...not.  We got about three-fourths of the way through taking down the stage before an accident happened.  If you know anything about building a stage or have been to the play, then you may understand this.

The Prescenium (sp?) arch at the front of the stage (closest to the audience) snapped in half and fell.  We think what happened was that the flat on the right side of the stage (the right side if you are looking at the stage from out in the audience) started to come loose while we were taking other parts and flats down.  Then the corner pointing away from the stage started swaying which then caused the arch to snap down near the flat on the left of the stage.  Upon snapping, the rope helping to support it broke and the flat fell.

Well almost everyone got out of the way of the flat.  Unfortunately, JB got caught underneath it.  I'm guessing she was trying to get out of its way but the flat came down to fast and trapped her.  Luckily she was only hurt a little bit...just some bruising.  I'm just glad she didn't get hurt worse.  The bruises are on her side and her arm around her elbow.

I'm also glad we didn't have much more to do after that.  O my, that was scary.  I'm glad she is okay.

Well I've got to go study now.  Later you guys.  Good luck on mid-terms.

This is a story written under the influence of boredom.  It was a game thought up by Toddles where you create a story with each participant contributing three word lines.  Here is the story...hope you enjoy.  If it offends anyone, too bad.  But take into account, we were not being serious what-so-ever when we wrote it.

To all my friends, I apologize if I do not seem like myself for the next couple of days.  I received some really depressing news this morning.  My mom called a little after 9am to talk with me and tell me that my great uncle (brother-in-law of my grandmother) had passed away.  Not expecting it to, this news hit me really hard.  I have been crying on and off all morning.  Right now I feel like I could still cry.  

While he was still in good health, I loved talking to him when I would see him at Thanksgiving.  He was a really good guy.  He would come over with his son (my cousin), Steve.  Mom is going to get Steve's address for me so I can write to him.  This past Thanksgiving, Casper (my great uncle) was not in the best of health.  He could barely walk and was hardly aware of anything around him.  But I guess I didn't think he would pass away this soon.  I miss him.  He was the last remaining WWII Veteran, that I know of, in my family.  This coming Thanksgiving will be different without him there.  It will be kind of weird to see Steve and not see Casper with him.  O I hope Steve does come this year.  If I knew how to post a picture in this blog I would show you guys a picture of him.  

Well I think I'm gonna go now.
Love to all,
Tari (aka Lauren)

Well, I guess it's about time for me to actually make a real post on here...after being prompted by several friends. So...what have I been up to lately? Not too terribly much. Just going to classes, being involved in extra curricular activities, trying to hang out with friends, and hanging out with my boyfriend. For any of you who may not know, Ronnie and I are back together. Although, in a way, we never really broke up...we just did not have the means to actually "see" one another over the summer. So if you wanna view it that way, Ronnie and I have sort of been together for about 7 months now. o.O 7 months...wow...that's the longest relationship I have ever been in. I hope it lasts...I really do love him. About a week ago, Ein was staying over in my room. Well the power went out at about 1:30 am. Sandy and I left my room at around 2:00 am because I didn't want to try and sleep with no real means to wake up by in the morning. I grab my half-dead flashlight and we head outside. We find T. and sit and talk with him for a bit. We run across another friend of mine and decide to trapes over to Cooper and see if Ronnie is awake. We get over there, my friend goes and knocks on Ronnie's door but gets no answer. We didn't know where Ronnie was. We then head back to Ellington and sit out on the brick wall for a bit. Around 3:00 am or so, I see someone come out of Ellington who looked a little familiar. Pointing my flashlight at the person to get a better look, it turned out to be Ronnie. Turned out his friend "D" had come over and kidnapped him when the power went out and they had been running around the campus. So then D., C., T., Ein, Ronnie, and I decide to walk about the campus. Upon passing by Clement, D. and C. want to go up to the 4th floor. Ein and I tell them "NO" and continue walking. They don't seem to understand why, we try to explain it to them. (more like yelled at them after telling them "no" three times.) After this, Ein, Ronnie, and I head over to Cooper and down to the basement, where we stayed until the power came back on at 4 am. That was a fun night. Wouldn't mind if it happened again but maybe next time it'll be on a weekend. anyone wanna go Transformer bowling next Saturday (after Fall break)?
